Date: Wed 9 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Scotsman, Wed 9 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=4229486>

Viet Nam: grandfather [asymptomatic] of avian influenza patients also infected
-----------------------------------------------
The grandfather of 2 siblings infected with avian influenza [virus] in Viet
Nam has also contracted the virus but has shown no symptoms of the disease
that has killed 46 people in the region. Health authorities suspect that
the 3 family members, from northern Thai Binh province, caught the virus
after eating an infected goose slaughtered by the grandfather a month ago
[February 2005], and there was no immediate indication that they had
infected one another.
Test results at the National Institute of Hygiene and Epidemiology in Hanoi
showed that the 80-year-old man was infected with the H5N1 avian influenza
virus. The man remains in good health at his home without any of the
disease's typical symptoms of high fever and breathing difficulties. His
21-year-old grandson and 14-year-old granddaughter are hospitalized in
Hanoi. None of the remaining 12 family members have tested positive for the
virus. Earlier this week [2nd week March 2005], Viet Nam reported that a
26-year-old male nurse, who cared for the grandson, had also been infected
by avian influenza virus, but health officials said it was likely he
contracted the disease outside the hospital. Health authorities suspect a
meal of goose the family had on 8 Feb 2005 was the source of the
infections. However, they ate chickens and geese several times during the
week-long Lunar New Year festival last month [February 2005].
Several cases in Viet Nam and Thailand have involved family clusters, where
several relatives were infected at the same time, though there has been no
evidence that the virus has mutated into a form easily transmitted by
people. Health officials warn that, when that happens, the virus could
spark a global pandemic that kills millions. So far, most human infections
have been traced to contact with sick poultry.
Viet Nam has had a total of 33 deaths from the deadly disease, 13 of them
in the latest outbreak which began last December [2004]. A woman in
Cambodia also died this year [2005] in a Vietnamese hospital. 12 people
have died in Thailand.
The grandfather has been given anti-viral drugs and asked to limit his
contact with other people, said Dao Trong Bich, Deputy Director of the
medical center in Thai Thuy District where the family lives. The man's
family had raised chickens, one of which died during Tet. The man then gave
the 3 remaining chickens to his daughter, the mother of the 21-year-old man
and his 14-year-old sister.
